## ROADMAP

*Bigger features and vision. Not immediate but planned.*

-----

### Venn Diagram Visualization Mode

A second visualization type alongside the current graph. The AI groups nodes into overlapping Venn diagram circles to show similarities and shared properties between domains rather than tensions and connections.

- User can toggle between Graph View and Venn View
- AI prompt needs a second output format for groupings
- Venn diagram rendered using D3.js or a dedicated library
- Great for showing where two domains share common ground vs where they diverge
- Could be a killer feature for academic and research users

-----

### Context-Aware Expansion (Future Architecture)

Each node click sends the entire existing map as context to the AI so it builds genuinely on what’s already there. Infinite AND coherent. Aligns with Fractal’s mission of not giving AI limited context.

- Higher token cost — only viable at paid Groq tier or self-hosted model
- Revisit when product has real users and token budget
- This is the architecture that makes Fractal feel like a thinking machine, not a static map

-----

### Raspberry Pi Local Dev Server

Shared team AI server so no one needs to run Ollama locally or use API credits during development. See AgentNotebook for full hardware specs and setup instructions.

- Pi 5 8GB + Coral TPU + Llama 3.2 3B
- ~5-10 seconds per map in dev
- ~$150 one time cost
- Set up after Sprint 5 when team is actively building daily

-----

### User Accounts and Saved Maps

- Save maps to an account
- Share maps via URL (network_serialize.js already built for this)
- Map history and revisiting past sessions
- Collaborative maps — multiple users on same map

-----

### Fine-Tuning Pipeline

Once real user maps are collected:

- Use Groq/GPT-4 to generate synthetic training data
- Collect engagement signals from real users
- Fine-tune Llama 3.2 on Fractal-specific map quality
- Self-host fine-tuned model to cut costs at scale

